GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 2
SENATE BILL 706
House Committee Substitute Favorable 6/25/25
Short Title: County Waste Management/Nonbetterment Costs. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
March 26, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO RESTORE ASSISTANCE TO COUNTIES WITH THE CLEANUP OF SCRAP
3 TIRES AND TO PROVIDE AN EXEMPTION FROM NONBETTERMENT COSTS FOR
4 CERTAIN MUNICIPALITIES.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1.(a) G.S. 105-187.19(b) reads as rewritten:
7 "(b) Each quarter, the Secretary shall credit thirty percent (30%) of the net tax proceeds to
8 the General Fund. Scrap Tire Disposal Account. In the event the amount in the Account exceeds
9 three hundred thousand dollars ($300,000) at the end of any fiscal year, such excess shall be
10 credited to the Highway Fund. The Secretary shall distribute the remaining seventy percent (70%)
11 of the net tax proceeds among the counties on a per capita basis according to the most recent
12 annual population estimates certified to the Secretary by the State Budget Officer."
13 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 130A-309.63 as it existed immediately prior to repeal is
14 reenacted and reads as rewritten:
15 "§ 130A-309.63. Scrap Tire Disposal Account.
16 (a) Creation. – The Scrap Tire Disposal Account is established as a nonreverting account
17 within the Department. Department of Environmental Quality. The Account consists of revenue
18 credited to the Account from the proceeds of the scrap tire disposal tax imposed by Article 5B of
19 Chapter 105 of the General Statutes.
20 (b) Use. – The Department may use revenue in the Account only as authorized by this
21 section.
22 (1) The Department may use up to fifty percent (50%) seventy-five percent (75%)
23 of the revenue in the Account to make grants to units of local government to
24 assist them in disposing of scrap tires. To administer the grants, the
25 Department shall establish procedures for applying for a grant and the criteria
26 for selecting among grant applicants. The criteria shall include the financial
27 ability of a unit of local government to provide for scrap tire disposal, the
28 severity of a unit of local government's scrap tire disposal problem, the effort
29 made by a unit of local government to ensure that only tires generated in the
30 normal course of business in this State are provided free disposal, and the
31 effort made by a unit of local government to provide for scrap tire disposal
32 within the resources available to it.
33 (2) The Department may use up to forty percent (40%) fifteen percent (15%) of
34 the revenue in the Account to make grants to encourage the use of processed
35 scrap tire materials. These grants may be made to encourage the use of
36 tire-derived fuel, crumb rubber, carbon black, or other components of tires for
*S706-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 use in products such as fuel, tires, mats, auto parts, gaskets, flooring material,
2 or other applications of processed tire materials. These grants shall be made
3 in consultation with the Department of Commerce, the Division of
4 Environmental Assistance and Outreach of the Department, and, where
5 appropriate, the Department of Transportation. Grants to encourage the use of
6 processed scrap tire materials shall not be used to process tires.
7 (3) The Department may use up to one hundred seventy-five thousand dollars
8 ($175,000) of the revenue in the Account for administrative costs and to
9 support a position to provide local governments with assistance in developing
10 and implementing scrap tire management programs designed to complete the
11 cleanup of nuisance tire collection sites and prevent scrap tires generated from
12 outside of the State from being presented for free disposal in the State.position
13 for implementation of the requirements of this Part.
14 (4) The Department may use the remaining revenue in the Account only to clean
15 up illegal scrap tire collection sites that the Department has determined are a
16 nuisance. The Department may use funds in the Account to clean up a
17 nuisance tire collection site only if no other funds are available for that
18 purpose.
19 (c) Eligibility. – A unit of local government is not eligible for a grant for scrap tire
20 disposal unless its costs for disposing of scrap tires for the six-month period preceding the date
21 the unit of local government files an application for a grant exceeded the amount the unit of local
22 government received during that period from the proceeds of the scrap tire tax under
23 G.S. 105-187.19. A grant to a unit of local government for scrap tire disposal may not exceed the
24 unit of local government's unreimbursed cost for the six-month period.
25 (e)(d) Reporting. – The Department shall include in the report to be delivered to the
26 Environmental Review Commission on or before 15 January of each year pursuant to
27 G.S. 130A-309.06(c) a description of the implementation of the North Carolina Scrap Tire
28 Disposal Act for the fiscal year ending the preceding 30 June. June 30. The description of the
29 implementation of the North Carolina Scrap Tire Disposal Act shall include the beginning and
30 ending balances in the Account for the reporting period, the amount credited to the Account
31 during the reporting period, and the amount of revenue used for grants and to clean up nuisance
32 tire collection sites."
33 SECTION 1.(c) G.S. 130A-309.64 is repealed.
34 SECTION 1.(d) G.S. 130A-309.06(c) reads as rewritten:
35 "(c) The Department shall report to the Environmental Review Commission and the Fiscal
36 Research Division on or before April 15 of each year on the status of solid waste management
37 efforts in the State. The report shall include all of the following:
38 …
39 (10) A description of the implementation of the North Carolina Scrap Tire Disposal
40 Act that includes the beginning and ending balances in the Scrap Tire Disposal
41 Account for the reporting period, the amount credited to the Scrap Tire
42 Disposal Account during the reporting period, and the amount of revenue used
43 for grants and to clean up nuisance tire collection under the provisions of
44 G.S. 130A-309.64.as required by G.S. 130A-309.63(d).
45 …."
46 SECTION 1.(e) G.S. 130A-309.09C(g) reads as rewritten:
47 "(g) In addition to any other penalties provided by law, a unit of local government that
48 does not comply with the requirements of G.S. 130A-309.09A(b), G.S. 130A-309.09A(d), and
49 G.S. 130A-309.09B(a) shall not be eligible for grants from the Solid Waste Management Trust
50 Fund Fund, the Scrap Tire Disposal Account, or the White Goods Management Account and
51 shall not receive the proceeds of the scrap tire disposal tax imposed by Article 5B of Chapter 105
Page 2 Senate Bill 706-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 of the General Statutes or the proceeds of the white goods disposal tax imposed by Article 5C of
2 Chapter 105 of the General Statutes to which the unit of local government would otherwise be
3 entitled. The Secretary shall notify the Secretary of Revenue to withhold payment of these funds
4 to any unit of local government that fails to comply with the requirements of
5 G.S. 130A-309.09A(b), G.S. 130A-309.09A(d), and G.S. 130A-309.09B(a). Proceeds of the
6 scrap tire disposal tax that are withheld pursuant to this subsection shall be credited to the General
7 Fund and may be used as provided in G.S. 130A-309.64. Highway Fund. Proceeds of the white
8 goods disposal tax that are withheld pursuant to this subsection shall be credited to the General
9 Fund and may be used as provided in G.S. 130A-309.83.Highway Fund."
10 SECTION 1.(f) G.S. 130A-309.54 reads as rewritten:
11 "§ 130A-309.54. Use of scrap tire tax proceeds.
12 Article 5B of Chapter 105 imposes a tax on new tires to provide funds for the disposal of
13 scrap tires, for the cleanup of inactive hazardous waste sites under Part 3 of this Article, and for
14 all the purposes for which the Bernard Allen Memorial Emergency Drinking Water Fund may
15 be used under G.S. 87-98. tires. A county may use proceeds of the tax distributed to it under that
16 Article only for the disposal of scrap tires pursuant to the provisions of this Part or for the
17 abatement of a nuisance pursuant to G.S. 130A-309.60."
18 SECTION 1.(g) This section becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to
19 quarterly crediting of the proceeds of the scrap tire disposal tax occurring on or after that date.
20 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 136-27.1 reads as rewritten:
21 "§ 136-27.1. Relocation of water and sewer lines of municipalities, nonprofit water or sewer
22 corporations or associations, local boards of education, and certain private water
23 or sewer utilities.
24 (a) The Department of Transportation shall pay the nonbetterment cost for the relocation
25 of water and sewer lines, located within the existing State transportation project right-of-way,
26 that are necessary to be relocated for a State transportation improvement project and that are
27 owned by: (i) a municipality with a population of 10,000 20,000 or less according to the latest
28 decennial census; (ii) a nonprofit water or sewer association or corporation; (iii) any water or
29 sewer system organized pursuant to Chapter 162A of the General Statutes; (iv) a rural water
30 system operated by a County as an enterprise system; (v) any sanitary district organized pursuant
31 to Part 2 of Article 2 of Chapter 130A of the General Statutes; (vi) constructed by a water or
32 sewer system organized pursuant to Chapter 162A of the General Statutes and then sold or
33 transferred to a municipality with a population of greater than 10,000 20,000 according to the
34 latest decennial census; (vii) a local board of education; or (viii) a private water or sewer utility
35 organized pursuant to Chapter 62 of the General Statutes serving 10,000 20,000 or fewer
36 customers.
37 (b) A municipality with a population of greater than 10,000 20,000 shall pay a percentage
38 of the nonbetterment cost for relocation of water and sewer lines owned by the municipality and
39 located within the existing State transportation project right-of-way that are necessary to be
40 relocated for a State transportation improvement project. The percentage shall be based on the
41 municipality's population, with the Department paying the remaining costs, as follows:
42 (1) A municipality with a population of greater than 10,000, 20,000, but less than
43 50,000, shall pay twenty-five percent (25%) of the cost.
44 (2) A municipality with a population of 50,000 or greater, but less than 100,000,
45 shall pay fifty percent (50%) of the cost.
46 (3) A municipality with a population of 100,000 or greater shall pay one hundred
47 percent (100%) of the cost."
48 SECTION 2.(b) This section is effective retroactive to January 1, 2025, and applies
49 to (i) nonbetterment costs arising after that date and (ii) nonbetterment costs arising before that
50 date but unpaid by a municipality on that date.
